Gmail (originally Google Mail) is a free, web-based email, search, and communication service developed by Google. It was first released in 2004 as a limited invitation-only service, and was made publicly available in 2005. Since its release, Gmail has grown to become one of the most widely used email services in the world.

The development of Gmail began in late 2003, when Sergey Brin, one of the founders of Google, had the idea of creating a free web-based email service that would be easy to use and would have a large storage capacity. He discussed the idea with his co-founder Larry Page and fellow engineer Paul Buchheit. They started working on the project in January 2004, using the code base of an existing email service called Pyra Labs. The team then recruited David Girouard from Pyra Labs to lead the project.

The name "Gmail" was chosen because it sounded like "Google mail". The team also considered using the names "Googletalk", "Googlemail", and "Gmail". The team felt that Gmail was a better choice because it was simple and easy to remember, and they wanted to avoid any association with Google's search engine.

In July 2004, Gmail was released as a limited invitation-only service for Google employees and students at Stanford University. In August 2007, Gmail became available to the public through a public beta program. In April 2009, Google announced that Gmail would be available to all users without the need for an invitation.

The development of Gmail continued throughout its early years. In February 2005, Google acquired Pyra Labs, which allowed them to add more features to Gmail such as labels, filters, and chat functionality. In October 2006, Google added integration with its other services such as Google Calendar and Google Docs. In November 2006, Gmail reached one billion messages per day, making it the fastest growing web application at the time. In May 2009, Gmail added support for attachments up to 25 MB and a new search functionality called OneBox. In February 2011, Gmail was redesigned with a more streamlined interface that focused on making it easier to use and navigate through email messages. In September 2015, Gmail introduced two new features: Smart Reply and Smart Compose. Smart Reply suggests pre-written responses that users can select with a single click while Smart Compose predicts what users are typing and suggests complete sentences or phrases based on what they have written so far.

Today, Gmail has over one billion active users worldwide and continues to grow in popularity due to its ease of use and features such as search functionality, automatic organization of emails into labels and categories, integration with other Google services such as Hangouts for messaging and Voice for phone calls, and spam filtering capabilities."
